                <exercise workspace="3in">
                    <title>The Intermediate Value Theorem</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>f: \R \to \R</m> be continuous, and let <m>a,b \in \R</m> with <m>a \lt b</m>.
                            If <m>y \in \R</m> is strictly between <m>f(a)</m> and <m>f(b)</m>, then
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            there exists <m>c \in \R</m> such that <m>a \lt c \lt b</m> and <m>f(c) = y</m>. 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            There is a useful picture of this fact in <url href="https://htmlpreview.github.io/?https://github.com/hulpke/csbook/blob/main/mathforcs.html#Ch5.S2">Section V.2</url>
                            of your textbook.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="4in">
                    <title>Application: Finding Zeros</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Is there a solution to <m>x^3-\cos(x) = 0</m>?
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            We can start by letting <m>f(x)= x^3-\cos(x)</m>, and noticing <m>f</m> is continuous (it is 
                            a combination of continuous functions). Since <m>f(0)=-1 \lt 0</m> and <m>f(\pi) = \pi^3+1 \gt 0</m>,
                            the IVT tells us there must exist <m>c</m> such that <m>0 \lt c \lt \pi</m> and <m>f(c) =0</m>. If we'd
                            like to approximate what <m>c</m> is even closer, we can repeat the IVT in a similar fashion (see notes
                            from class).
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
