            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Practice: IVT</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Use the Intermediate Value Theorem to approximate a solution to <m>x^3 + x + 3 = 0</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            We know <m>f(x) = x^3 + x + 3</m> is continuous since it is a polynomial. We could start by noticing
                            that <m>f(0) = 3</m> and <m>f(-2)= -7</m>. Therefore, the IVT tells us there must exist <m>c \in (-2,0)</m>
                            such that <m>f(c)=0</m>. The midpoint of the interval <m>(-2,0)</m> is <m>-1</m>, so we can compute
                            <m>f(-1) = 1 \gt 0</m>. Therefore, the IVT tells us there must exist <m>c \in (-2,-1)</m> such that 
                            <m>f(c) = 0</m>. Repeating four more times would tell us that <m>c \in (-1.25, -1.1875)</m>. Compare this
                            to the actual value of <m>c \approx -1.21341</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
